<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,824,1353]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">
Hence, the total figure of both hemisternites (
<figureCitation box="[705,786,824,849]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 21" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1954,1977]" captionTargetBox="[196,1373,204,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[185,1395,193,1935]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 21. Basidissus bendai sp. nov., female holotype: 15, head, dorsal view; 16, pronotum, lateral view, scheme; 17, proximal part of pronotum, dorsal view, scheme; 18, right antenna; 19, hemisternites, ventral view; 20, toothed plate with stylus, lateral view, seen in situ; 21, toothed plate, dorsal view, seen in situ. Scale bars in mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285118/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">
Fig. 
<number box="[757,786,825,849]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
) is the reconstruction of a natural state. Medial and lateral rods long and slender. Apex of each hemisternite with robust, strongly sclerotized toothed plate (
<figureCitation box="[1283,1424,860,885]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 21" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1954,1977]" captionTargetBox="[196,1373,204,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[185,1395,193,1935]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 21. Basidissus bendai sp. nov., female holotype: 15, head, dorsal view; 16, pronotum, lateral view, scheme; 17, proximal part of pronotum, dorsal view, scheme; 18, right antenna; 19, hemisternites, ventral view; 20, toothed plate with stylus, lateral view, seen in situ; 21, toothed plate, dorsal view, seen in situ. Scale bars in mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285118/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">
Figs. 
<number box="[1350,1424,861,885]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75" value="20.0" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="19.0">19–21</number>
</figureCitation>
). Toothed plate consists of four teeth, apical one longest, two basalmost teeth partly fused. Lateral face of toothed plate with robust stylus (which is movable) anchored in distinctly membranous area (also see Comments).
</paragraph>
