<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="75" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,824,1353]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,968,993]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Etymology.</emphasis>
Patronym, dedicated to our friend and colleague Pavel Benda, director of the Bohemian 
<collectingCountry box="[151,285,1004,1029]" name="Switzerland" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
National Park (
<collectingCountry box="[461,643,1004,1029]" name="Czech Republic" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Czech Republic</collectingCountry>
) and member of the 
<number box="[875,931,1005,1029]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75" value="2013.0">2013</number>
Czech-Madagascan expedition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="75" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,824,1353]" box="[199,1311,1040,1065]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1040,1065]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Distribution.</emphasis>
East 
<collectingCountry box="[414,551,1040,1065]" name="Madagascar" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, Andasibe-Mantadia National Park, Analamazaotra forest (
<figureCitation box="[1214,1296,1040,1065]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 23. 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1285,1308]" captionTargetBox="[151,1410,193,1262]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1265]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 23. 22, type localities of Basidissus species in Madagascar; 23, distribution of Basidissus cristatus in Madagascar." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285119/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">
Fig. 
<number box="[1267,1296,1041,1065]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,824,1353]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,469,1076,1101]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[484,693,1077,1101]" class="Insecta" family="Anthribidae" genus="Basidissus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bendai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[484,693,1077,1101]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Basidissus bendai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[708,806,1076,1101]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[708,806,1076,1101]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is easily the smallest known species of the genus. Moreover, it differs from all other species by its totally different colour pattern and characters in the key (
<figureCitation box="[1326,1392,1112,1137]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1940,1963]" captionTargetBox="[175,1415,230,1926]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[175,1417,195,1934]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Madagascan Basidissus species, dorsal view, 1, B. bendai sp. nov., female holotype (3.0 mm); 2, B. cirrifer Frieser, 2000 (7.2 mm); 3, B. cristatus Fairmaire, 1897 (4.9 mm); 4, B. fulvitarsis Frieser, 2007 (4.6 mm); 5, B. incilis Frieser, 2000 (6.1 mm); 6, B. senilis Frieser, 2000 (6.5 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285115/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1405,1421,1113,1137]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[187,1363,208,1927]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1365,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Madagascan Basidissus species, lateral view, 7, B. bendai sp. nov., female holotype (3.0 mm); 8, B. cirrifer Frieser, 2000 (7.2 mm); 9, B. cristatus Fairmaire, 1897 (4.9 mm); 10, B. fulvitarsis Frieser, 2007 (4.6 mm); 11, B. incilis Frieser, 2000 (6.1 mm); 12, B. senilis Frieser, 2000 (6.5 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285116/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="75" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,824,1353]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1148,1173]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Comments</emphasis>
. A detailed study of the female terminalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[839,1041,1149,1173]" class="Insecta" family="Anthribidae" genus="Basidissus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bendai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[839,1041,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">Basidissus bendai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1048,1138,1148,1173]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1048,1138,1148,1173]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
has clearly shown that the stylus on the toothed plates is movable, anchored in a circular membranous part of the toothed plate and surrounded by a group of strong, curved setae (
<figureCitation box="[684,822,1220,1245]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 21" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1954,1977]" captionTargetBox="[196,1373,204,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[185,1395,193,1935]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 21. Basidissus bendai sp. nov., female holotype: 15, head, dorsal view; 16, pronotum, lateral view, scheme; 17, proximal part of pronotum, dorsal view, scheme; 18, right antenna; 19, hemisternites, ventral view; 20, toothed plate with stylus, lateral view, seen in situ; 21, toothed plate, dorsal view, seen in situ. Scale bars in mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285118/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="75">
Figs. 
<number box="[748,822,1221,1245]" pageId="4" pageNumber="75" value="20.5" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="20.0">20–21</number>
</figureCitation>
). We assume that the stylus on the toothed plate of the hemisternites (if present and not extremely reduced) of the female genitalia of most anthribids could be generally movable. This character has not been studied so far, or has generally been overlooked and requires more detailed study in future.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
